SunsetMidnight

Target IP: 192.168.186.88

Scanning


There are three ports on the target machine: SSH, HTTP, and MySQL. From the scan above, it states the vhost name of the target machine is sunset-midnight. I will append this to the /etc/host first. I will begin enumeration with the HTTP application.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The target host is running a WordPress website on port 80 as shown above. Viewing the source-code of this page states the host is running 5.4.2 version of WordPress. After doing multiple directory search and finding nothing useful.

Port 3306: MySQL

While performing enumeration on port 80, I ran hydra to bruteforce the password of user root. And this worked, as I obtained the password robert.


There is an interesting database called wordpress_db. This database contains a table called wp_users. There is one entry inside this called, and it contains the hash password of the user admin. When looking up the type of hash online, it states it is WordPress (MD5). I was unable to crack this hash.

Exploitation


I decided to change the passwrd to admin using the SQL syntax update wordpress_db.wp_users set user_pass='21232f297a57a5a743894a0e4a801fc3' WHERE user_login='admin';. I can now use admin:admin to gain access to the WordPress application!


And now I have access to the WordPress application using admin:admin.


Since the application allows Theme Editor, I used this gain a reverse shell connection. I replaced the 404.php file with PHP Pentest Monkey reverse shell inside the twentytwenty theme.


I started a listener on port 8443 and browsed to http://sunset-midnight/wp-contents/themes/twentytwenty/404.php to activate the connection! And now I have a foothold on the machine!

Privilege Escalation


The wp-config.php file contains the username jose and password.


Before attempting to crack the hash, I attempted to login using jose:645dc5a8871d2a4269d4cbe23f6ae103 with SSH and it worked!


Apparently, there is an interesting binary called /usr/bin/status. Running strings on this binary shows it calls the service binary without including its path. Meaning we can exploit this using path abuse misconfiguration.


And now I am root.
